<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I just hate the fact that people yelling wolf are getting EQ gimped down to some simple mindless single-player-game-like (Diablo2 comes to mind) where you don't even need social interaction (remember the &quot;class interdependance&quot; where did it go?). <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Class interdependance is not gone, though with the gimp luclin xp mobs they came close to killing it, they're just trying to focus it on combat now instead of the overall immersive experience.  <br>
<br>
Honestly after 60 levels of running through the Karanas, Ocean of Tears, Dreadlands, Burning Woods, IceClad, Great Divide, Wakening Lands, and Maidens Eye I'm glad that the tedium of travel is gone.  I don't think that level 1s should have access to the plane of knowledge, but I don't think something like Travel-interdependancy is something sacred that needs to hold true for the entire length of the game.<br>
<br>
Things lose their novelty..  I can honestly believe that if they had <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">boats</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> in Planes of Power that most people would not enjoy them one tiny bit.  When you first ride a boat it's actually pretty cool.  Soon it gets to be a mildly boring chore but helps keep people separated on the world.  Eventually it becomes a maddening time sink.  If you've ever played Final Fantasy you'll notice that your ability to travel increases as you progress through the game.  Early on, exploration is emphasized, while the end game focuses on combat and story. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=eelyen>Eelyen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<BR>Jesus? No, but I'm<BR>his brother Eelyen.</span><br>  Posts: 1619<br> <font color=#ffffff>(2/11/03 9:15 am)</font><br>     <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: EQ is dying</span><hr size=1> Honestly, I think Everquest is far better off Today then it was a few years ago.  There is tons more available to the casual gamer and the hardcore gamer alike. <br>
<br>
Planes of Power was designed to seperate the top guilds somewhat.<br>
<br>
With Planes of Power and the current state of the game, getting to level 65 is not all that hard for a determined person.  And with the added levels and AA's of the game.  Even the more casual guilds are getting there piece of the higher end game.  While, I admit, there are no casual guilds killing Emperor, farming Vex Thal, or doing Rallos Zek.  They are getting more NToV runs, Tormax's, etc.  <br>
<br>
It's true they aren't getting the best loot in the game.  But there really is no way to provide the best loot in the game to the casual gamer, and still keep the hardcore gaming aspect valid.  And if they did provide small encounters that provided the best loot, the hardcore gamers would just monopolize it and then the casual gamers would complain about it. <br>
<br>
The casual can't expect the most out of the game with the way it's designed.  The hardcore gamers play for the very reason of beating the most challenging encounters and getting rewarded with the loot that is equal of that encounter. <p><HR Width="25%" Align="Left">
